WEBVTT

00:04.233 --> 00:10.603
Dr. Thomas, would you tell us about some of the ways 
that you have gone about raising money for

00:04.233 --> 00:10.603
research endeavors?

00:14.709 --> 00:23.702
Well, now you're talking just generally about 
raising money for research, or are you talking

00:14.709 --> 00:23.702
about specifically for the center here? For the 
center here. For the center. Okay.

00:29.912 --> 00:33.497
Well, the... The main objective when you have a new 
organization such as this is and has been, you have

00:34.692 --> 00:44.523
to establish your credibility. And you have to get 
your name before those who sponsor work.

00:52.351 --> 01:04.024
And we were

00:52.351 --> 01:04.024
very fortunate in having early on a relationship 
with Professor John Erickson of the University of

00:52.351 --> 01:04.024
Edinburgh in Scotland, who is a, well, John is 
probably one of the Western world's foremost

01:04.477 --> 01:20.292
experts in the Soviet Union and Soviet military 
history. And, well, he is a Kremlinologist, as

01:20.332 --> 01:26.398
some of them are called. And so we were lucky in 
hooking up with him very early. John's fame in the

01:34.750 --> 01:43.623
U.S. and around the world brought us some degree of 
notoriety rather early on. In essence, we rode

01:45.346 --> 01:53.058
John's coattails into this new arena that Texas 
A&M had decided to try to enter. And then, in

01:54.320 --> 02:03.053
addition to that, it was a question of trying to 
identify problems that were of national or

02:03.303 --> 02:14.196
international interest and addressing those 
problems and showing people that, in fact, we

02:03.303 --> 02:14.196
could do work of this type. I think we've had some 
success in that.

02:21.926 --> 02:29.175
Of course, you have to understand that there is a 
certain amount of huckstering to this whole

02:21.926 --> 02:29.175
business.

02:30.708 --> 02:45.801
One of the problems that you have with a young 
professor, you say a young assistant professor

02:30.708 --> 02:45.801
who has just gotten his PhD, and he comes to Texas 
A&M, and he realizes that in order to get ahead

02:30.708 --> 02:45.801
here, why, you've got to learn to bring in money. 
What he doesn't realize is that the

02:47.263 --> 02:58.993
business of bringing money does not depend 
strictly on one's technical ability. A lot of

03:00.813 --> 03:16.276
these young fellows think that in order to get 
money that all they have to do is to write out a

03:00.813 --> 03:16.276
proposal, a technically excellent proposal, and 
send it off to the National Science Foundation or

03:00.813 --> 03:16.276
NASA or DOD and say send money by return mail. Well, 
it just doesn't happen that way. You have to sell

03:19.461 --> 03:20.763
yourself. You have to convince the sponsor that 
you're capable of doing good work and that you will

03:28.100 --> 03:29.442
that you'll do some good for him. Chances are he's a 
bureaucrat. He functions in that mode. He is

03:35.372 --> 03:43.184
judged by his effectiveness and by the impact of 
the money that he dispenses to others. Obviously,

03:43.945 --> 03:54.242
if a guy sits up there and gives money to people who 
don't perform, he's not going to have money to give

03:43.945 --> 03:54.242
to them very long. So the business of raising 
research is a combination of

03:54.982 --> 04:07.337
competence and marketing and huckstering and so 
forth. And some academicians recoil at that. They

04:10.561 --> 04:14.285
think, well, it just ought to be Simon Pure. And you 
ought to be judged strictly on your merits, your

04:14.446 --> 04:17.790
technical merits. And I suppose that would be nice 
if that's the way it was. But unfortunately,

04:21.394 --> 04:24.718
that's not the way it is. So we, the past two years 
then, I have spent an awful lot of time in

04:25.255 --> 04:48.767
Washington and other places, and

04:25.255 --> 04:48.767
just telling people about the Center, telling 
them about Texas A&M, because, you know, this

04:25.255 --> 04:48.767
Texas A&M has been, down over the years, a kind of a 
parochial university. It, of course, being a

04:49.948 --> 04:54.334
land-grant school, why it it felt responsive to 
the needs of the state. And so as a result, it has not

05:00.024 --> 05:09.499
been nationally involved for many years. And so 
the center here sort of represents one of Texas

05:10.741 --> 05:23.781
A&M's efforts to become nationally involved and 
internationally involved.

05:23.963 --> 05:33.891
But there was just an awful lot of people that had 
seen Texas A&M's football team on the field and had

05:23.963 --> 05:33.891
seen the Corps of Cadets and didn't really 
understand that, you know. I should say the

05:36.213 --> 05:41.078
marching band and the military aspects of the 
university. But just surprising how many of those

05:42.679 --> 05:53.228
folks needed to understand what Texas A&M was and 
what it was like and the fact that it is not just

05:42.679 --> 05:53.228
another pretty university. And so there's been a 
lot of that, and essentially just the business of

05:55.493 --> 06:04.746
establishing credibility and so forth. But it 
has, oh, I'm pleased with what we've accomplished

06:04.766 --> 06:16.562
to date, and I guess we'll get into that later, but 
we've still got quite a ways to go. What are some of

06:17.243 --> 06:21.949
the sources of funding that the research 
department has brought here? Well,

06:23.228 --> 06:37.683
the bulk of the funding from outside,

06:23.228 --> 06:37.683
well, I guess we need to back up now a little bit. And 
you need to understand the way the center has been

06:37.703 --> 06:45.230
structured for most of its existence. That is 
where we have had a series of groups within the

06:46.271 --> 06:52.037
center.

06:53.333 --> 07:00.563
Until

06:53.333 --> 07:00.563
prior to the first of June of this year, we had the 
Industrial Economics Group. It draws its funding

07:02.306 --> 07:10.778
largely from cities and other entities around 
over the state of Texas.

07:12.961 --> 07:21.012
So the city of Del Rio, for example, or let's see, I 
guess actually it was the COG, the Council of

07:12.961 --> 07:21.012
Governments around Del Rio, hired the industrial 
economics group back a year ago to do an industrial

07:21.650 --> 07:28.060
base study. And that means they go in there and they 
try to delineate all of the elements of the

07:29.201 --> 07:38.215
economic base for that region of the state. And of 
course, they were wondering what they could do to

07:39.637 --> 07:42.221
broaden that. And they were wondering 
specifically about how important an element of

07:42.361 --> 07:49.311
tourism was and how to beef that up. And so our 
people went in there and made the appropriate

07:50.000 --> 07:57.467
surveys and recommendations and presented that 
to the folks down there. So that funding came from

07:57.487 --> 08:03.874
the four or five county region around Del Rio. And 
they've done similar things for the city of Orange

08:05.475 --> 08:10.460
and the city of Big Spring and so forth. And if you 
interview John Roberts, who now heads the revised

08:10.520 --> 08:17.307
industrial economics division, a separate 
entity now, why he can tell you more about that.

08:22.694 --> 08:39.351
Then we have an urban group, which essentially 
tries to help city administrations around over

08:22.694 --> 08:39.351
the state, trying to increase the efficiency of 
the delivery of city government services to the

08:22.694 --> 08:39.351
citizens.

08:42.193 --> 08:44.055
Some of their funding comes from the cities. Some 
of it came from the National Science Foundation,

08:48.995 --> 08:56.845
which provided funding to set up something called 
the Texas Innovation Group, which is a group of

08:48.995 --> 08:56.845
around 40 cities that work together.

08:59.848 --> 09:07.498
Then we had this education group, and the bulk of 
their funding, their work deals largely with the

08:59.848 --> 09:07.498
CETA program. And so they have what we call 
pass-through money. It's federal money that

09:11.943 --> 09:17.550
comes from the, I guess, from the Office of 
Education, Department of Education, and comes to

09:18.290 --> 09:21.734
the governor, and then from the governor to us. And 
then we have a special studies group, and they were

09:23.376 --> 09:41.377
involved in hurricane response modeling, trying 
to, among other things, figure out how to evacuate

09:23.376 --> 09:41.377
Galveston Island in the teeth of a large 
hurricane. Now that money came partly from the

09:42.558 --> 09:46.643
state and partly from NOAA. the National Office of 
Atmospheric and National Oceanic and

09:47.602 --> 09:54.615
Atmospheric Administration. I'll get it right 
here shortly. And also we have a man here who is an

09:57.280 --> 10:08.361
expert in some of these exotic crops like Wai'uli 
and jojoba. Waiuli is a little shrub that grows

