you spell that? Sotillo, S-A-L-T-I-L-L-O.

10:49.644 --> 10:56.893
And

10:49.644 --> 10:56.893
that money for Dan's work had come from the 
National Science Foundation. And, let's see,

10:58.575 --> 11:02.800
then in the defense group, which of course is the 
sort of really the main reason that the center

11:03.640 --> 11:06.724
exists. The bulk of that money comes from DOD. I 
should say not the bulk of it, all of it comes from

11:10.990 --> 11:15.356
DOD currently. And a large part of it from the 
Office of Net Assessments,

11:15.376 --> 11:25.530
which is part of the Office of Secretary of 
Defense. And then we now have a program that is

11:26.371 --> 11:32.161
being funded by the Defense Intelligence Agency. 
That's DIA, not CIA.

11:37.510 --> 11:50.151
And we've also done some work for the Foreign 
Technology Division at Wright-Patterson, which

11:37.510 --> 11:50.151
is the descendant of the old organization that I 
worked for up there, the Air Technical

11:37.510 --> 11:50.151
Intelligence Center. You mentioned earlier that 
some of the research work that the center does is

11:50.958 --> 12:07.427
unclassified

11:50.958 --> 12:07.427
because of the military sensiveness of the- It's 
classified because of the- Excuse me,

11:50.958 --> 12:07.427
classified. I have the wrong word. Is any of this 
information, can it be obtained through the

12:11.054 --> 12:15.582
Freedom of Information Act? I don't know enough 
about the legal ramifications of it. I would guess

12:22.198 --> 12:22.979
not. I know that there's a controversy underway in 
Congress now that a bill has been introduced to

12:23.239 --> 12:31.111
exempt the CIA from this Freedom of Information 
Act. Yes, uh-huh. Do you have any ideas on that?

12:34.697 --> 12:37.501
Yeah, I'm afraid I'll reveal some biases here. Of 
course, you know in the wake of Watergate and so

12:37.682 --> 12:45.754
forth, there was a some dismantling of our 
intelligence operations,

12:46.848 --> 12:56.423
a move that I think has gone far too far.

12:59.788 --> 13:12.788
And there was established this Freedom of 
Information Act which guaranteed access to

12:59.788 --> 13:12.788
certain classified or guarded material.

13:14.084 --> 13:21.415
And, of course, it established several oversight 
committees in Congress to look over the shoulder

13:14.084 --> 13:21.415
of CIA. That, by and large, has been a disaster 
because congressmen being the political

13:22.416 --> 13:37.037
animals, and senators, I don't mean just 
representatives, but being the political

13:22.416 --> 13:37.037
animals they are, they just can't keep their 
mouths shut.

13:38.013 --> 13:57.133
And we have, I think we have severely damaged the 
position and stature of the United States by

13:38.013 --> 13:57.133
dismantling essential parts of our intelligence 
apparatus and by permitting people to leak secret

13:38.013 --> 13:57.133
material.

13:59.715 --> 14:02.518
And it's been a sad operation. Now then, I would 
have to say that there very likely were excesses,

14:03.820 --> 14:27.548
abuses of that power that the CIA had and that the 
so-called imperial presidency had,

14:03.820 --> 14:27.548
but I worry less about that, frankly. I think I 
would rather see perhaps some modest abuse of

14:30.511 --> 14:39.742
power in contrast to a completely open situation. 
I just don't agree that the press has a right to know

14:40.122 --> 14:44.728
everything. And I think, you know, the pendulum 
swings and we'll find the correct position here

14:46.269 --> 14:57.703
eventually, but we're not there yet. Let me ask 
you, do you know in numbers about how many other

15:00.616 --> 15:09.588
universities have similar centers for strategic 
technology that Texas A&M has? Or is this a rare

15:09.608 --> 15:12.672
phenomenon, relatively rare? Well, it all 
depends on how rigidly or broadly you define the

15:12.692 --> 15:17.278
word similar. There are outfits that do Soviet 
Warsaw Pact research work. At Harvard there is an

15:27.346 --> 15:30.670
outfit called the Russian Research Center. 
Probably one of the better known organizations is

15:33.352 --> 15:39.679
the Hoover Institution, which is affiliated with 
Stanford University. The Mershon Center at Ohio

15:41.001 --> 15:42.783
State. Mershon, M-E-R-S-H-O-N Center at Ohio 
State is pretty well known.

15:55.443 --> 16:03.732
Center for Strategic Studies at Georgetown 
University in Washington is very well known. And

16:04.693 --> 16:13.983
there is a Center for International Studies, I 
guess they call it, in Florida. I think it's at the

16:15.064 --> 16:19.088
University of Florida at Gainesville, I believe, 
but I'm not sure about that. And so, yes, there are

16:19.726 --> 16:28.439
similar kinds of organizations that is similar in 
terms of the type of work that they do. Now, our

16:29.641 --> 16:36.130
philosophy, our operational philosophy, 
however, is rather different than those. So this

16:37.272 --> 16:41.939
is where I get in the business of being a little bit 
more specific about the word similar.

16:45.224 --> 16:47.607
One of the reasons that the Center exists is that we 
had been encouraged by some fairly high-ranking

16:48.397 --> 16:55.826
military officers to get into this game. And what 
they were telling us was that some of the existing

16:57.469 --> 17:15.872
think tanks, and there are those who refer to us as 
the Aggie think tank, and I guess that's to some

16:57.469 --> 17:15.872
extent true, but some of the existing, that most of 
the existing think tanks had had gotten caught up

17:17.422 --> 17:20.285
in the Washington scene. There are two large ones 
which are not affiliated with universities, the

17:22.807 --> 17:33.418
RAND Corporation, R-A-N-D, and of course, the 
Brookings Institute in Washington. They've been

17:33.438 --> 17:40.585
in this business a long time, as well as these other 
university things. But what we were told was that

17:41.546 --> 17:47.412
they have been in the business so long, and they 
have become so much a part of the Washington scene

17:48.910 --> 17:50.652
that they'd begun to feed on one another. And I know 
from my experience when I was at the University of

17:51.894 --> 18:01.327
Maryland and being in the Washington area that 
these people all attend the same cocktail

17:51.894 --> 18:01.327
parties. They attend the same briefings. And, 
well, as a result, there's just no fresh thinking

18:04.872 --> 18:09.158
that comes out of them. And so this was one of the 
things that we were told very clearly, that the

18:10.539 --> 18:18.310
nation needed a new boy on the block. to do some 
fresh thinking, and somebody that was not a part of

18:19.606 --> 18:24.331
the Washington scene. And we sure as the deuce 
qualify on that basis.

18:30.137 --> 18:45.994
Beyond that, one very high-ranking military 
officer told me, he said, you know, Dick, he said,

18:30.137 --> 18:45.994
he said our track record in terms of predicting and 
evaluating Soviet actions and intentions has not

18:30.137 --> 18:45.994
been good. And And one of the main reasons for that 
is the so-called mirror image syndrome, which is a

18:49.981 --> 19:13.933
view that the Soviet Union sees the world the way we 
do, a view that believes that they respond to

18:49.981 --> 19:13.933
pressures the way we would, that they want the same 
things in the world that we do, and that's just flat

18:49.981 --> 19:13.933
wrong. They think differently. They act 
differently. They believe differently. And a lot

19:21.658 --> 19:35.172
of our erroneous assessments of the USSR has 
derived from that mirror image syndrome. And I had

19:36.473 --> 19:45.722
had a brush with that when I was at ATIC way back 
before I went back to do my graduate I can tell you

19:46.327 --> 19:47.408
more about that. It involves some classified 
stuff, but I can give you an unclassified

19:48.189 --> 19:54.696
description of it. But from the beginning then, my 
view has been that we were not going to fall into

19:54.716 --> 20:02.784
that trap. That we were, to the extent that we 
could, we were going to learn how to think Soviet.

20:09.871 --> 20:14.376
In other words, when an issue or a problem came up, 
we're going to try to try to think about it the way

20:14.761 --> 20:16.683
the Soviets would. And this is a rather different 
viewpoint than any of these other institutions

20:18.285 --> 20:24.833
have. Yeah, I notice you have a Soviet map on the 
wall behind you here, so that's to give you that

20:24.853 --> 20:30.280
perspective. That's right. That's right. And

20:33.724 --> 20:43.215
Professor Erickson at the University of 
Edinburgh, who I mentioned earlier, has been very

20:33.724 --> 20:43.215
important in this because course John you know 
he's a brilliant man speaks six languages

20:44.073 --> 21:12.139
including Russian fluently travels in Russia 
extensively and his view is that it doesn't make

20:44.073 --> 21:12.139
any difference whether you're talking about 
Afghanistan or you're talking about space

20:44.073 --> 21:12.139
warfare or you're talking about Poland or or what 
that the in order to understand

21:12.372 --> 21:15.755
the way the Russians operate, you have to 
understand the Soviet psyche. And I regret to say

21:17.717 --> 21:20.860
we have not spent a lot of time doing that. We spent a 
lot of money studying the accuracy of their

21:20.940 --> 21:34.853
missiles, and we can tell you how accurate they 
are, and we can tell you how fast their airplanes

21:20.940 --> 21:34.853
fly, and we can tell you how thick the armament is on 
their, the armor plating is on their tanks, and so

21:20.940 --> 21:34.853
forth. But when you come to study the Soviet 
military man, the guy who pulls the trigger or

21:40.790 --> 21:55.165
pushes the button or gives the order or the people 
that back him up, we really don't understand a

21:40.790 --> 21:55.165
great deal about the Soviet Union. And so that's 
one of the underlying philosophies that we have

21:55.185 --> 22:06.797
here, that we're going to make our studies, every 
one that we do, just as broad as we possibly can. And

22:08.144 --> 22:16.355
so one of the messages that I carried to people who 
would sponsor our work was that philosophy. And I

22:16.375 --> 22:32.037
had to tell them, if you give us money to study, say, 
Soviet moves toward space warfare capability,

22:16.375 --> 22:32.037
we're not going to limit it just to the 
technological studies. We're going to try to

22:32.097 --> 22:35.502
understand the people that make the decisions 
that undergird that whole effort? And where are

22:38.681 --> 22:45.271
the research institutes that supply that 
technology? How do Brezhnev and the Politburo

22:45.291 --> 22:49.637
feel about that? What sort of policy views do they 
have? What are the decision-making processes

22:53.582 --> 22:59.951
that underlie all of that? And so we tackle things 
rather broadly here. uh then there was another

23:06.785 --> 23:34.007
another element to this thing too i mentioned to 
you that that there were some high-ranking people

23:06.785 --> 23:34.007
and and also i i've talked about the military but 
but we had well i have a former student who's on the

23:06.785 --> 23:34.007
staff of the senate armed services committee he's 
an a m graduate and of course he uh he works now for

23:06.785 --> 23:34.007
senator tower and and uh And he has some very strong 
views, and he's in a unique position to observe a

23:34.460 --> 23:43.312
lot of this stuff. And from him and from others, 
even military people, they

23:43.452 --> 23:57.531
admitted that they had been part of the problem 
here. That is to say that in the past, an outfit

24:04.278 --> 24:10.646
would come to the military in Washington to get 
money to do a piece of research work. And this, more

24:12.749 --> 24:15.413
often than not, was not a university outfit. It 
would be typically one of what we call the Beltway

24:15.453 --> 24:27.308
Bandits, which is the array of little 
organizations, R&D organizations, that dot the

24:15.453 --> 24:27.308
Beltway around. What was that word? Beltway 
Bandits, they called them. And they're outfits

24:31.126 --> 24:38.496
who sell their services to the Pentagon and to 
other agencies in Washington. Well, if one of

24:38.516 --> 25:00.087
these outfits came to the Pentagon and got a chunk 
of money,

24:38.516 --> 25:00.087
in the process of negotiating the contract and 
talking about the work, the Pentagon, the

24:38.516 --> 25:00.087
military officers would tell the outfit, in 
essence, what they thought the answer would be

24:38.516 --> 25:00.087
when they completed this research. More often 
than not, lo and behold, that was in fact the answer

25:03.047 --> 25:07.032
that showed up.

25:12.078 --> 25:15.863
And I don't know that there was anything 
necessarily malicious about this. It was just

25:15.963 --> 25:17.825
something that happened. And so there was a crying 
need for objectivity in a lot of these studies. and

25:27.404 --> 25:31.991
a crying need for an organization that would 
simply call a spade a spade. And if you came up with

25:32.552 --> 25:41.385
an answer that was somewhat different than what 
the sponsor thought it was going to be, well,

25:32.552 --> 25:41.385
that's the way it was. In short, it was hoped that we 
could avoid a position where we might be judged to

25:43.829 --> 25:56.247
be intellectual prostitutes, more or less.

25:57.155 --> 26:05.186
So there was one other element to this thing that I 
might mention that deals with your comment about

25:57.155 --> 26:05.186
classified material.

26:08.471 --> 26:20.648
I know when I was in this game first, way back years 
ago,

26:08.471 --> 26:20.648
there was an awful lot of open literature stuff 
that is unclassified material that came across my

26:08.471 --> 26:20.648
desk. But being young and impressionable, Of 
course, I saw top secret stuff, too, and stuff that

26:25.606 --> 26:30.152
was classified beyond that. And I thought that the 
top secret stuff was a hell of a lot more valuable

26:31.594 --> 26:39.185
than the open stuff. The open literature just 
wasn't worth anything because it was open. Well,

26:44.552 --> 26:46.115
that's wrong. That's an erroneous view. And of 
course, the Russians now publish and disseminate

26:48.217 --> 26:55.107
an awful lot of literature about themselves. and 
so one of the things that again this was to some

26:56.521 --> 27:19.153
extent the Erickson influence on us Erickson 
works only with open literature and and he knows an

26:56.521 --> 27:19.153
awful lot about what is going on in Russia and he 
understands of course an awful lot about the

26:56.521 --> 27:19.153
Soviets and so Another of our operational 
philosophies here is that we will mine the open

27:20.247 --> 27:26.715
literature assiduously. And yeah, we'll do 
classified work, but we don't necessarily think

27:27.637 --> 27:37.249
that the answers are all in classified documents. 
And so we do, the bulk of our work to date has been

27:37.269 --> 27:45.981
unclassified open literature searches. Could 
you touch briefly on Maybe some study that's being

27:48.850 --> 27:53.315
undergone now or has recently been completed.

