Yeah, we can give you two or three examples. That'd 
be sufficient, thank you. Okay. First of all,

28:02.286 --> 28:16.562
the Pentagon has asked us here to, this was an 
offshoot of the Erickson program,

28:16.964 --> 28:23.634
set up a so-called program of excellence for the 
study of Soviet military organizations and

28:16.964 --> 28:23.634
personnel. And the first study that was 
undertaken in that program was a study of Soviet

28:25.977 --> 28:33.929
military districts. The Soviet Union is divided 
up into about 16 military districts.

28:43.143 --> 28:44.625
They are unique. organizational entities. 
There's nothing else like it anyplace else in the

28:46.850 --> 28:49.894
world. Well, I take that back. I guess the Chinese 
have military districts, but they are relatively

28:51.576 --> 29:00.527
recent developments.

29:03.931 --> 29:14.123
However, the military districts in the Soviet 
Union existed back in czarist times.

29:15.250 --> 29:34.429
They represent

29:15.250 --> 29:34.429
an effort on the part of the Soviet military to 
bring the military right down to grassroots

29:15.250 --> 29:34.429
control and grassroots involvement throughout 
the USSR. We don't really understand how they

29:35.971 --> 29:42.878
function, especially in wartime.

29:43.837 --> 30:07.701
and you have to understand that the invasion of 
afghanistan was not done by the soviet army it was

29:43.837 --> 30:07.701
done by the two adjoining military districts the 
turkestan military district and the central

29:43.837 --> 30:07.701
asian military district and so they now i don't 
mean to infer that they are autonomous in some

29:43.837 --> 30:07.701
areas they are you see military training in the 
soviet union starts in the second grade And the

30:09.520 --> 30:18.794
local military districts have the 
responsibility for that training program for

30:09.520 --> 30:18.794
Soviet school children. In that sort of a 
function, they are relatively autonomous. But I

30:23.080 --> 30:32.094
surely don't mean to infer that the two commanders 
of the military districts got together and said,

30:23.080 --> 30:32.094
hey, let's invade Afghanistan. No, that's not 
yet. They are linked directly to the Ministry of

30:35.609 --> 30:42.958
Defense in Moscow, and the Ministry of Defense 
calls the shots. But an awful lot of the logistics

30:43.078 --> 30:53.711
and the rear services and supply and a fair amount 
of the troop supply come from the military

30:43.078 --> 30:53.711
districts. So it's a kind of a unique and odd 
organizational entity. And so our study here was

31:00.179 --> 31:05.565
to try to understand how those military districts 
function uh what they uh what they do what they

31:06.625 --> 31:35.046
don't do how much how much autonomy do they have and 
they are disparate in their in their

31:06.625 --> 31:35.046
organizational structure some of them are quite 
complex others are fairly simple some of them will

31:06.625 --> 31:35.046
have civil defense responsibilities some of them 
do not so it's kind of an odd odd quirk so we are just

31:06.625 --> 31:35.046
now in the final stages of actually what will turn 
out to be a first part of a two-stage study of Soviet

31:35.262 --> 31:44.170
military districts. We had thought initially it 
would just be one element, which would be largely

31:44.230 --> 31:51.577
historical.

31:54.179 --> 32:03.227
However, the second element, which we will do next 
year, will deal with what we call the military

31:54.179 --> 32:03.227
districts in the mobilized mode, which will look 
at what in fact has happened to those two military

32:03.933 --> 32:08.277
districts adjoining Afghanistan. There had also 
been some movements involving the military

32:09.298 --> 32:16.465
districts adjoining Poland. And so perhaps from 
that we can glean some information on how those

32:16.705 --> 32:25.094
things function during wartime. And so that's one 
study that

32:26.475 --> 32:33.822
will be completed shortly. We have a series of 
so-called casual papers which deal with Soviet

32:34.898 --> 32:48.475
command structure, command changes, and the 
personalities involved. The idea here is, again,

32:48.495 --> 32:53.302
it's just a business of trying to learn how the 
Soviets think. When a commander changes his...

33:01.223 --> 33:06.591
his position, that is, when he's given a new 
command or moves within the military structure.

33:08.093 --> 33:30.606
We'll go back and get information on his 
background, where he was born, where he went to

33:08.093 --> 33:30.606
school, what kind of military schools did he go 
through, if we can find it, what were his parents

33:08.093 --> 33:30.606
like, and try to get some idea of his background and 
his training.

33:31.075 --> 33:37.101
And then we'll have a complete review of the 
military posts that he has been assigned to. And

33:37.121 --> 33:52.355
then we will, if we can find three or four papers 
that he has authored over the past, say, ten years

33:37.121 --> 33:52.355
in military journals or whatever, we'll 
synopsize those papers. But when you put that all

33:53.016 --> 33:59.682
together, it makes a fascinating package, 
because here is this guy. Oh, we recently did one on

34:00.151 --> 34:02.254
General Majorov. And

34:02.955 --> 34:09.445
here's this guy sort of laid out before you. And so 
you can see his background and his training. And

34:15.815 --> 34:29.415
then when you look at some of his recent writings, 
which are synopsized, you get some idea of what

34:15.815 --> 34:29.415
he's thinking about and what his main concerns 
are. And these generally will establish some sort

34:30.172 --> 34:36.160
of a pattern. And so it can be fairly revealing. So 
we've published, I guess, three or four studies of

34:37.903 --> 34:42.509
that type.

34:45.674 --> 34:54.747
Then a study that is just now being published 
switches over to the US side.

34:56.089 --> 34:59.233
There are about 10 materials. which are labeled 
strategic. These are metals which are very

35:02.642 --> 35:07.949
important to the U.S. military. Cobalt is one of 
them. When you add cobalt to steel, it makes it very

35:12.175 --> 35:14.858
hard. It also increases its magnetic properties 
and increases its high temperature

35:15.399 --> 35:26.554
characteristics, which means that it's very 
useful for turbine engines and things like that.

35:27.817 --> 35:33.604
It's also very useful in electronic components 
because of its magnetic enhancement

35:27.817 --> 35:33.604
capabilities. Currently the U.S. gets, 
depending on what year you look at, anywhere from

35:34.966 --> 35:46.901
75 to 95 percent of its cobalt from Zaire in Central 
Africa, Southern Africa. And there's a whole

35:47.162 --> 35:50.466
array of these things, tantalum, titanium, And a 
lot of people think that oil is the only material

35:52.268 --> 35:58.837
where we are at the mercy of other people. That's 
wrong.

36:03.183 --> 36:18.023
So we've done a study of

36:03.183 --> 36:18.023
looking at what the U.S. might do in the event of a 
protracted conflict with the Soviets.

36:19.066 --> 36:30.301
There is more and more thinking now that when war 
comes, that it will not be a nuclear war, that it

36:19.066 --> 36:30.301
will be a protracted non-nuclear war. And so the 
question is, the U.S. military needs cobalt in

36:30.641 --> 36:46.002
sufficient amount to build jet engines and other 
war materiel. for the duration of that

36:46.758 --> 36:50.023
non-nuclear war. And if the Soviets could choke 
off our supply from South Africa, from Southern

36:51.344 --> 37:06.946
Africa, I should say, which they could fairly 
easily do, then where in the name of God do we get the

36:51.344 --> 37:06.946
cobalt? And so the title of the study is Cobalt, 
Strategic Alternatives for Supply. And there are

37:14.990 --> 37:19.215
four alternatives for supplying cobalt. And I 
won't take time here to delineate all of that. But

37:23.199 --> 37:27.504
what it amounts to is that there is cobalt here in 
the U.S. and Canada. There had been cobalt mines

37:28.324 --> 37:32.389
here, usually associated with copper mines. But 
because of the economics of the situation, it was

37:33.510 --> 37:38.335
cheaper to buy it from Zaire and ship it in here. And 
so all of our cobalt mines have been shut down,

37:38.515 --> 37:42.279
copper mines. So we need to reopen them. It turns 
out that the country that has more cobalt than any

37:45.668 --> 37:52.475
other country in the world is Cuba. Well, in the 
event of a protracted non-nuclear conflict with

37:54.757 --> 38:03.646
the Soviets, are we going to permit them to operate 
from that base there 90 miles from our shore? One

38:05.307 --> 38:06.168
would think not. One would hope not. I'm not 
espousing an invasion of Cuba, necessarily, on

38:08.791 --> 38:12.975
the other hand. I think to try to pretend that Cuban 
cobalt does not exist is stupid. And so one of our

38:19.599 --> 38:36.079
recommendations that came out of this report was a 
suggestion that in our strategic planning that we

38:19.599 --> 38:36.079
take into account the fact that Cuba does have 
those magnificent cobalt reserves and plan

38:19.599 --> 38:36.079
accordingly. Were these reserves being unused at 
this time? Oh, yes. The Soviets are using them. You

38:40.064 --> 38:40.465
bet. They get 40% of their cobalt from Cuba. And, of 
course, using plants that were originally

38:44.967 --> 38:49.671
American-built in pre-Castro days. And then 
after Castro took over, of course, they were

38:50.832 --> 38:57.538
nationalized in an organization called, set up 
called, Cubanico. And it's an arm of the Cuban

38:58.719 --> 39:01.401
government. And so they sell, as a matter of fact, 
that's one of the main elements of the Cuban

39:01.421 --> 39:08.787
economy, that and sugar, cobalt and sugar. And so 
it... It's a situation that I think has to be looked

39:15.764 --> 39:20.489
at realistically. I might add that in this report, 
in this study that we did, we made an estimate of the

39:22.050 --> 39:28.837
amount of cobalt that the U.S. would need. And of 
course, the U.S. has been stockpiling cobalt and

39:30.018 --> 39:37.144
has about 40 million pounds of cobalt in our 
stockpile currently. Our estimates indicate

39:39.166 --> 39:45.012
that that would be about adequate for the first 
year of a conflict. Which would be all right. I

39:46.288 --> 39:47.230
mean, that's great. That gives us a year or two to do 
some other things. The question is, what are the

39:50.755 --> 39:52.658
other things you're going to do? And so I think if we 
could reopen US mines with more efficient

39:53.920 --> 40:06.559
extraction processes, then perhaps be prepared 
to use the Cuban nickel somewhere or other. And

40:06.659 --> 40:12.568
those strategies are beyond my consideration. I 
think all we can do is just simply point out that

40:13.122 --> 40:17.107
it's there and it needs to be considered. And it's 
amazing. I've previewed this report before some

40:19.350 --> 40:22.334
people in Congress. They said, Cuba? Nickel? Why 
didn't somebody tell us? And so this is, I think,

40:27.361 --> 40:35.913
another evidence of the kind of fresh thinking 
that is needed in some of these areas.

40:38.696 --> 40:41.340
There are some other things that we'll be getting 
into. Later on, we, of course, here at Texas A&M, we

40:41.692 --> 40:51.104
are very strong in the energy field, particularly 
in natural gas, crude oil production, that sort of

40:41.692 --> 40:51.104
thing. We're also very strong in manufacturing, 
and manufacturing is undergoing a revolution now

40:52.126 --> 41:02.019
with computer-aided systems coming into the 
scene. And so we will be doing some of those kinds of

41:03.221 --> 41:11.091
studies in the Warsaw Pact and in the USSR. And then 
there is one other program that will begin this

41:12.320 --> 41:20.491
fall, which will deal with space warfare. And 
there is some very clear evidence that the Soviets

41:21.893 --> 41:30.285
are moving heavily in this direction with the 
development of laser and particle beam weapons.

41:31.286 --> 41:36.353
As a matter of fact, they are, according to the 
evidence, they are probably ahead of the U.S. in

41:31.286 --> 41:36.353
that area. So we've been asked by the US Air Force to 
make a study of some aspects of the US space program

41:36.839 --> 41:59.726
and try to give some recommendations as to what 
kinds of new technologies need to be developed in

41:36.839 --> 41:59.726
order to allow the US to fight and win a war in space. 
OK, in closing, is there any other comment that

42:01.207 --> 42:06.053
you'd like to make about anything regarding the 
center your activities? Oh, I guess only this. As I

42:11.369 --> 42:19.438
said earlier in the interview, the Center here 
represents a new effort for Texas A&M. It

42:19.498 --> 42:31.112
represents a new frontier, a new way in which Texas 
A&M can serve the people of the state of Texas and

42:19.498 --> 42:31.112
the people of the United States. I think, and of 
course it's a biased view, I think Texas A&M's star

42:31.379 --> 42:36.527
is rising. I think with all due respects to our 
friends in Austin, I think Texas A&M is becoming

42:36.907 --> 42:47.483
the premier institution in the Southwest. And so I 
think the center can help contribute to that image

42:49.125 --> 42:56.115
and to that structure. And also, I would hope the 
Center can do something else. You know, there are,

43:04.790 --> 43:16.827
of course, many influences on the federal scene, 
and many of us feel that the influence of the

43:04.790 --> 43:16.827
Northeast and the Midwest has exceeded their 
importance in the general scheme of things. It

43:18.169 --> 43:29.685
seems like when anybody is appointed to a high post 
in the government, why, he comes from MIT or

43:18.169 --> 43:29.685
Caltech or someplace. And that's not to say that we 
want Texas or the Southwest to run everything,

43:30.509 --> 43:35.916
necessarily. On the other hand, we think that 
there needs to be more of a balanced voice in some of

43:36.717 --> 43:46.971
these national decision-making processes. And 
so I think there is a role here for the center to

43:48.133 --> 43:51.697
play. Of course, here again, I'm not suggesting 
that we don't have good representation in

43:52.218 --> 43:59.588
Congress or anything like that. we do have. On the 
other hand, one cannot lose people like LBJ and

44:01.965 --> 44:11.760
Connolly and Olin Teague and Sam Rayburn and so 
forth without losing a hell of a lot of clout. You

44:12.261 --> 44:17.589
know, our young people are bright and articulate 
and so forth, but they just don't have the clout

44:12.261 --> 44:17.589
that those old boys had. And so, here again, I think 
that an outfit like the Center can contribute to

44:17.609 --> 44:27.263
that, and Texas A&M, of course, has as its first 
mission the education of young people in the state

44:27.800 --> 44:37.914
of Texas, and that must remain the first objective 
for this institution. But close behind that, I

44:39.135 --> 44:53.014
think, has to be a program to serve the people of the 
state of Texas and, indeed, the people of the

44:39.135 --> 44:53.014
United States in other ways, and in ways that a 
truly intellectual institution can. And so I

44:54.344 --> 44:58.269
think the center can aid in that. And so we have 
fairly lofty goals. But you know how Aggies are.

45:06.399 --> 45:08.161
We'll just swat the hell out of things. And it 
doesn't make any difference whether this is a

45:08.321 --> 45:13.047
lofty goal or not. We're going to give it our best 
shot, and we're going to win. Thank you very much

45:16.932 --> 45:20.577
for this most enlightening interview, Dr. 
Thomas. Thank you.

